answers.body_markdown:
If two threads call `CreateEncryptedData` with the same key at the same time, there are three possible outcomes:

1. `CalulateEncryptedData()` is called exactly once, both threads get the result, and that result is stored in `_blobs`.
2. `CalulateEncryptedData()` is called twice, but the result of one of the calls is discarded. Both threads get the same result, and that result is also stored in `_blobs`.
3. `CalulateEncryptedData()` is called twice, and both threads get different results. One of the results is stored in `_blobs`. Obviously this is undesirable.

If you need case 1, then you need a separate lock object, but you can write it like this:

    public string CreateEncryptedData(string key)
    {
        if (_blobs.TryGetValue(key, out var value))
            return value;

        lock (_encryptedDataLock)
        {
            return _blobs.GetOrAdd(key, x =&gt; CalulateEncryptedData());
        }
    }

If case 2 is OK, you can further simplify to this:

    public string CreateEncryptedData(string key)
    {
        return _blobs.GetOrAdd(key, x =&gt; CalulateEncryptedData());
    }

